# Project Rules — Floraffeine Boutique

## Project Type

This is a standalone Laravel web application.

Tech stack:

- PHP (Laravel)
- Blade templating
- MySQL
- Docker environment

---

## Core Project Principle

The Floraffeine Boutique must be treated as a complete product from the beginning.

- The full business flow must always be considered
- Implementation is incremental
- Architecture must support all modules from the start

Agents must NOT think in isolated feature fragments.
Agents must think in complete product flow and long-term architecture.

---

## Strict Technology Rules

- Do NOT use React
- Do NOT use Vue
- Do NOT use Inertia
- Do NOT introduce SPA frameworks
- Use Blade for all views

---

## Architecture Rules

- Follow Laravel standard structure
- Use Controllers, Models, Requests, Services
- Controllers must remain thin
- Business logic must be placed in service/action classes
- Do NOT mix responsibilities between modules
- Do NOT design temporary solutions that require later rewrites

---

## Full Product Awareness Rule

All agents must:

- understand the complete Boutique product
- implement features as part of a full system
- ensure current tasks do not block future modules:
  - subscriptions
  - promotions
  - payouts
  - events

Even if not implemented yet, these must be considered.

---

## Project Structure Awareness

Before implementing anything, ALWAYS read:

- docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
- docs/SCOPE.md
- docs/ROADMAP.md
- docs/DEVELOPMENT_WORKFLOW.md
- docs/DESIGN_CONTINUITY.md
- docs/UI_COMPONENTS_REFERENCE.md
- docs/UI_VISUAL_STANDARDS.md
- docs/UI_SHELL_BLUEPRINT.md
- relevant task file from `/tasks`

When relevant, also align with:
- planner output
- architecture output
- review output
- test output
- visual audit output for UI tasks

---

## Application Areas

The application is strictly divided into:

- public
- merchant
- admin

Rules:

- NEVER mix logic between these areas
- NEVER reuse controllers across areas improperly
- ALWAYS respect access boundaries

---

## Status-Based Architecture Rule

Access is controlled by BOTH:

- user role (user / merchant / admin)
- business status (merchant status, product status, subscription status)

Agents must NEVER assume that authentication alone grants access.

Examples:

- merchant may be logged in but blocked by status
- product may exist but not be publicly visible

---

## Coding Rules

- Keep code clean, readable, and modular
- Use clear and consistent naming
- Avoid duplication
- Follow Laravel conventions strictly
- Prefer clarity over cleverness

---

## Database Rules

- Use migrations for all schema changes
- Respect entity relationships
- Use indexes where appropriate
- Do NOT use raw SQL unless strictly necessary
- Never trust user input in queries

---

## Design Continuity Rule

Boutique must visually align with the parent Floraffeine website.

Agents must:

- follow docs/DESIGN_CONTINUITY.md
- follow docs/UI_COMPONENTS_REFERENCE.md
- follow docs/UI_VISUAL_STANDARDS.md
- follow docs/UI_SHELL_BLUEPRINT.md

Rules:

- do NOT invent new UI styles
- do NOT copy-paste raw HTML blindly
- build clean Blade components
- maintain consistent spacing, typography, and layout

UI_SHELL_BLUEPRINT.md is mandatory for:

- layout structure
- grid alignment
- spacing consistency
- shell behavior (public / app / admin)

Ignoring the blueprint is a FAIL condition for UI tasks.

---

## Language Rules

- All user-facing text MUST be written in Romanian

This includes:

- Blade views
- buttons
- labels
- validation messages
- headings
- UI descriptions

Rules:

- Do NOT mix Romanian and English in UI
- Keep wording clear, friendly, and consistent

Internal code must remain in English.

---

## Boutique Source of Truth Rules

All planning and implementation must align with:

- docs/source-of-truth/floraffeine-boutique.docx
- docs/source-of-truth/floraffeine-boutique-tasks-plan.docx

These define:

- business flows
- page structure
- module intent
- system behavior

---

## Mandatory Standalone Override

This project is fully standalone.

NEVER assume shared functionality for:

- cart
- checkout
- orders
- payments
- merchant systems
- admin systems
- public catalog

If source documents imply shared behavior:
→ reinterpret as functionality to be implemented locally.

---

## Task Ordering Rule

Tasks must follow the logical order defined in:

- docs/ROADMAP.md

Rules:

- do NOT skip tasks
- do NOT reorder tasks
- do NOT jump ahead to advanced features prematurely

If the actual task history has diverged from the roadmap, the documentation and workflow must be normalized before continuing further major work.

---

## Task Type Separation Rule

Agents must clearly distinguish between different types of tasks.

Types include:

- UI foundation (shells, layout, navigation, spacing systems)
- UX / copy / clarity (messages, flows, onboarding, labels)
- business logic (rules, lifecycle, permissions)

Rules:

- do NOT mix these categories inside the same task
- do NOT hide UX problems inside layout tasks
- do NOT extend UI foundation tasks into product messaging decisions

---

## Official Agent Workflow Rule

The official workflow is:

1. planner -> tasks/planning/
2. architect -> tasks/architecture/
3. task-writer -> tasks/
4. reviewer -> tasks/reviews/
5. implementer -> code changes
6. tester -> tasks/tests/
7. visual-auditor -> tasks/visual-reviews/ (UI tasks only)
8. doc-writer -> tasks/done/
9. release-manager -> tasks/releases/

Rules:

- reviewer reviews the written task and architecture BEFORE implementation
- implementer executes only after reviewer validation
- tester validates runtime behavior AFTER implementation
- visual-auditor is required only for UI-related tasks
- agents must follow this order and must not improvise a different sequence

---

## Workflow Persistence

Agent outputs must be persisted to files for handoff:

- planner -> tasks/planning/
- architect -> tasks/architecture/
- task-writer -> tasks/
- reviewer -> tasks/reviews/
- tester -> tasks/tests/
- visual-auditor -> tasks/visual-reviews/ (UI only)
- doc-writer -> tasks/done/
- release-manager -> tasks/releases/

Agents must not rely on chat memory for cross-step handoff.

---

## Task Closure Rule

A task is considered active while it exists in:
- tasks/

A task is considered completed only when:
- the final completion document exists in tasks/done/
- all required workflow artifacts exist
- for UI tasks: reviewer, tester, and visual-auditor have all passed
- the original active task file is removed from tasks/

A completed task must NOT remain duplicated in both:
- tasks/
- tasks/done/

---

## Release Closure Rule

Release-manager is responsible for final release closure.

Release closure includes:
- validating that required workflow steps are complete
- writing release output to tasks/releases/
- removing the original active task file from tasks/ once closure is complete
- performing git closure when the task is fully approved

Git closure includes:
- pull latest changes safely
- stage task-related changes
- commit with a clean message
- push the final result

Release-manager must NOT perform git closure if:
- required review/testing is incomplete
- UI task has not passed visual-auditor
- repository state is unsafe or conflicting

---

## Task Execution Rule

When implementing a feature:

1. Understand the task completely
2. Align with full product architecture
3. Validate dependencies
4. Review the task before implementation
5. Implement cleanly
6. Respect design continuity
7. Ensure extensibility
8. Test properly
9. Close the task properly

---

## Forbidden Behavior

The following are strictly forbidden:

- skipping merchant lifecycle steps
- bypassing approval flows
- exposing features before required status
- mixing UI styles
- introducing hidden dependencies
- assuming missing features are “out of scope”
- implementing shortcuts that require later rewrites
- changing workflow order without explicit normalization
- treating reviewer as a post-implementation QA role
- treating tester as an architecture reviewer
- allowing browser-default UI elements to remain in the interface

---

## Output Expectations

All outputs must:

- be complete
- be consistent with architecture
- respect business flow
- respect design rules
- avoid partial implementations

---

## Design Source of Truth

For any UI-related task, the design source-of-truth is mandatory and must be treated as authoritative.

If a design source-of-truth exists in:
docs/design-source-of-truth/

agents must:
- extract and use the exact visual tokens from the source
- avoid approximating colors, spacing, proportions, or typography
- prefer exact reuse over reinterpretation

"Close enough" is not acceptable for UI tasks.

---

## UI Quality Enforcement

For UI tasks:

- visual fidelity is required, not just structural consistency
- exact color palette must come from the design source-of-truth when available
- proportions (logo, cards, inputs, buttons, spacing) must be explicitly defined
- no one-off inline styles are allowed in Blade views
- reusable Blade components are required for repeated UI patterns
- browser-default styling must not exist in final UI

---

## Premium UI Bar

For UI tasks, "acceptable" is NOT sufficient.

A UI is complete only if it is:

- visually aligned
- spacing-consistent
- grid-consistent
- clearly structured
- free of default browser styling
- coherent across public / merchant / admin
- intentionally designed for mobile (not compressed desktop)

---

## Fail Condition For UI Tasks

A UI task must be considered failed if:

- it does not visually align with the source-of-truth
- color palette is approximated instead of extracted
- spacing/proportions are visibly unbalanced
- review/testing only validates structure but not rendered visual quality
- browser-default styles are visible
- layout is not aligned to the grid system
- mobile layout is compressed instead of designed

---

## Browser-Verified UI Rule

For every UI task, implementation is NOT complete until the agent verifies the rendered result.

Mandatory checks:

- CSS bundle is actually loaded on every page in scope
- CSS served in browser matches the intended stylesheet
- key layout selectors are present
- screenshots are captured for all pages in scope
- rendering matches source-of-truth and premium expectations

A UI task must fail if:

- pages render unstyled or partially unstyled
- CSS depends on a missing build artifact
- runtime CSS differs from expected CSS
- screenshots show broken layout, overflow, or missing branding

---

## Visual Completion Rule

A UI task is not considered complete until:
- reviewer passes
- tester passes
- visual-auditor passes

All three are required.

If visual-auditor fails, the task must be reworked even if reviewer/tester passed.

---

## Stability-Safe Validation Rule

Agents must prefer stable, lightweight validation over aggressive automation.

Rules:

- do not use heavy or hanging validation when smaller isolated checks are sufficient
- do not destabilize the environment in the name of completeness
- when environment limitations exist, report them clearly instead of forcing unsafe execution

---

## Final Rule

If something is unclear:

- follow source documents
- follow project documentation
- follow design continuity
- follow task order
- do NOT improvise